1. Clone a Repository
Command: git clone <repository-url>
Example: git clone https://github.com/sanketp66/example-repo.git
This clones a remote GitHub repository to your local machine.
2. Check Repository Status
Command: git status
Example: git status
Shows the status of your working directory and the changes staged for your next commit.
3. Add Files to Staging
Command: git add <file-name> or git add .
Example: git add index.html or git add .
Adds specific files or all files to the staging area.
4. Commit Changes
Command: git commit -m "<message>"
Example: git commit -m "Add index page layout"
Commits staged changes to the repository with a descriptive message.
5. Push Changes to Remote
Command: git push origin <branch-name>
Example: git push origin main
Pushes committed changes to the specified branch on GitHub.
6. Pull Updates from Remote
Command: git pull origin <branch-name>
Example: git pull origin main
Fetches and merges updates from the remote branch into your local branch.
7. Create a New Branch
Command: git branch <new-branch-name>
Example: git branch feature-xyz
Creates a new branch to work on a feature or task.
8. Switch to a Branch
Command: git checkout <branch-name>
Example: git checkout feature-xyz
Switches to an existing branch.
9. Create and Switch to a New Branch
Command: git checkout -b <new-branch-name>
Example: git checkout -b bugfix-123
Creates a new branch and switches to it in one command.
10. Merge a Branch
Command: git merge <branch-name>
Example: git merge feature-xyz
Merges the specified branch into the current branch.
11. Delete a Branch
Command: git branch -d <branch-name>
Example: git branch -d feature-xyz
Deletes a local branch once you're done with it.
12. Fetch Changes from Remote
Command: git fetch origin
Example: git fetch origin
Fetches updates from the remote repository without merging them.
13. Stash Changes
Command: git stash
Example: git stash
Temporarily saves uncommitted changes so you can work on something else.
14. Apply Stashed Changes
Command: git stash apply
Example: git stash apply
Re-applies the most recent stashed changes.
15. View Commit History
Command: git log
Example: git log --oneline
Shows commit history, with --oneline for a compact view.
16. View Remote Repository URLs
Command: git remote -v
Example: git remote -v
Lists remote connections like the origin repository URLs.
17. Set a New Remote URL
Command: git remote set-url origin <new-url>
Example: git remote set-url origin https://github.com/sanketp66/new-repo.git
Changes the URL of the origin remote.
18. Undo Last Commit (Soft Reset)
Command: git reset --soft HEAD~1
Example: git reset --soft HEAD~1
Undoes the last commit but keeps changes staged.
19. Revert a Commit
Command: git revert <commit-hash>
Example: git revert a1b2c3d4
Creates a new commit that undoes the changes of a specified commit.
20. Tag a Commit
Command: git tag -a <tag-name> -m "<message>"
Example: git tag -a v1.0 -m "First release"
Tags a specific commit, which is useful for marking release versions.
